===Etymology===
late 14c., variant of [[Wikipedia:British English|British English]] {{m|en|connexion}}, from English ''conneccion'', later ''connexioun'' (mid-15c.), from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|connexion}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|connexionem}} (nominative {{m|la|connexio||a [[conclusion]], [[binding]] [[together]]}}), from {{m|la|connectō}}, an alternative spelling of {{m|la|cōnectō||I [[bind]] [[together]]}}, from compound of {{m|la|co-||[[together]]}} and {{m|la|nectō||I [[bind]]}}

In [[American English]] mid-18c., spelling shifted from {{m|en|connexion}} to ''connection'' under influence of English {{m|en|connect}}, abetted by {{m|en|affection}}, {{m|en|direction}}, etc., thus making {{m|en|connexion}} British dated and ''connection'' in international use.

